\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 A series of trading expeditions began, which made the Stroganovs so enormously wealthy that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93the kindred of Anika knew no ends of their goods.\u8221\'94 Indeed, they gained so much by this exploitation that they began to fear the application by the Czar\u8217\'92s agent of a monetary test of patriotism. So, by a stroke of finance not unknown in modern days, there was arranged the Russian equivalent for carrying five thousand shares of Metropolitan. A block of small wares for the account of the Czar\u8217\'92s brother-in-law, Boris, was added to the stock in an especially important expedition among the Samoieds and Ostiaks. The adventurers got far inland. They saw men riding on elks, and sledges drawn by dogs. They returned with wonderful tales of marksmanship, and, more important, brought back enough furs to give Boris a dividend, in gratitude for which he secured to the Stroganovs the grant of an enormous tract of land along the Kama River and a monopoly of the trade with the aborigines.}
